Text.Value: I was going to ask you the same question.
As I was plummeting to certain death, I spied a glimmer quite near where I estimated my body to impact with less-than-savoury propulsion.
That's it! Go on, keep pulling!

EditorData.AnimationTags: [ChristianD] PLYR grabs Gale's arm and tries to pull Gale out of the sigil

Text.Value: *As soon as the dreams cross the threshold of your imagination, you snap back to realise they have all come true.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: You see the stump of the arm is on the ground, bloody. A terrible cry of anguish is heard behind the waypoint as the magic sparkles and the sigil becomes dormant.

Text.Value: Harder! Come on, put your back into it!

EditorData.AnimationTags: [ChristianD] PLYR's hands slips off Gale's arm. Lost balance a little and back to neutral stance (StandL).

Text.Value: You don't happen to be a cleric, by any chance, do you? A doctor? Surgeon? Uncannily adroit with a knitting needle?
You've grown none the wiser, I see.
Oh, but I see now you're travelling with plenty of company already. Perhaps I can join you later instead.
Most excellent. A parasite shared is a parasite halved. Or something to that effect.
No! I'm slipping away! I'll perish in here!

EditorData.AnimationTags: [ChristianD] PLYR's hands slips off Gale's arm in the attempt, causing the PLYR to lose balance and fall back.

Text.Value: Then you leave me no choice but to answer your folly with fury.
You don't trust this man. Draw your weapon.
*The magic around the sigil hisses like a cornered cat. Your only option now, is to grab the hand and pull.*
Decline.
I quite agree, but I have the unfortunate suspicion your survival is still very much in jeopardy.
No use sugarcoating it, is there?

EditorData.AnimationTags: [ChristianD] When the PLYR is easing out from the pain, the PLYR looks towards the sigil and noticed there's a lower arm out of the sigil looking for something to hold on. Then the hand opens up looking for help.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: (Cine) Next, in the centre of the sparks, you suddenly see a hand and lower arm coming out of the sigil. The hand opens and closes, looking for something to hold on to. A voice resounds, or so it seems, from deep within the stone.

Text.Value: Never mind the nautiloid. How did you get stuck in that stone?
I suppose few enough can. It's not exactly a common affliction.
Whatever you're doing, it's working wonders! Now a quick little pull should do the trick.
It was an act of foresighted kindness I assure you, for I have the feeling ample opportunities will present themselves for me to return the favour.
Fair enough. But even so, I have the unfortunate suspicion your survival is still very much in jeopardy.
A cap would keep the parasite nice and cosy, but its comfort is hardly my priority.
Still, swashbuckling heroics aside, I have the unfortunate suspicion your survival is still very much in jeopardy.
*This branch of flesh is begging to be pruned, and its sap supped from.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The Dark Urge goes into a spiral

Text.Value: With a keen, but calculated twist, you attempt to sabotage the sigil.
You were supposed to lend a hand, not take one.
It's far too dangerous. Leave him to his fate.
The currents of Weave around these sigils are absolutely fascinating. So much to explore!
As a githyanki, it's no news to you that this parasite will soon turn us into mind flayers - an outcome I'd rather like to avoid.
How about you? How did you survive the fall?
Are you certain? There might be danger around the next corner, and a wizard is excellent company to keep.
And I'm flattered, I'm sure - but it seems you're travelling with a substantial amount of companions already. Maybe later, yes?
I'd thank you for bringing me back to life, but your ending it in the first place has me rather in two minds about you.
I survived. That's all that matters.
Attack.
That said, despite my return to the land of the living my predicament remains, and so of course does yours.
It is a valuable commodity, to be favoured so by the gods.
And yet, if we indulge in the hypothetical for a moment...
Oh! But before you think you're about to embark on a journey with most ill-mannered a man: thank you for pulling me out of that stone.
I was, yes.
I don't know what transpired exactly, but the ship broke into pieces and I suddenly found myself in freefall.
No need to apologise. Are you all right?
I took control of the ship, landed it safely and saved the day.
Ow! Perhaps I should have clarified. A helping hand? Anyone?
Muster your strength and yank harder.
I'll perish...!

EditorData.AnimationTags: [ChristianD] Gale's arm movement is screaming for help as his hand is being pulled back in by the sigil. The PLYR rushes forward to reach for the hand but it's too late as Gale's arm completely dissapears into the sigil's sparkles.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: (Cine) The hand disappears into the sparkles and the sigil becomes dormant. A cry of 'I'll perish!' echoes several times, sounding increasingly far away, like an echo. Then silence.

Text.Value: I'll make my way to your camp, and embark upon a succulent slow-cook to be consumed upon your return.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [ChristianD] with all the PLYR's might, they manage to pull Gale out of the sigil. PLYR falls backward and Gale stumble out of the sigil before regaining his balance.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: (Cine) You pull with all your might, and slowly the upper arm starts to emerge from the sigil. Then suddenly Gale stumbles out from the stone, wobbling a bit before regaining his balance.

Text.Value: *You approach the sigil on the stone. Magic glitters and swirls from it erratically, as if malfunctioning. It looks slightly dangerous.*
Slap the hand.
I'm a cleric indeed, but I'm afraid the power to remove this parasite eludes me. I can't cure us.

RuleGroup.RuleString: BARD or DRUID or PALADIN or RANGER

Text.Value: I can tend to basic wounds and ailments, but alien parasites? I'm afraid not.
My hands are better suited to less delicate pursuits. I can offer you a swift end, but I can't cure you.
My patron offers me many gifts, but tadpole extraction is not one of them. I can't cure our parasites.
I possess many gifts, but tadpole extraction is not one of them. I can't cure our parasites.
I'm no stranger to high-stakes extractions, but these tadpoles are beyond even my light fingers. I can't cure us.
These tadpoles are beyond even my arcane knowledge. I cannot remove them.
Let flow some words of prayer to soothe the sigil's magic.
The insertee we speak of, this parasite - are you aware that after a period of excruciating gestation it will turn us into mind flayers?
Hail your party leader, would you? I'd like to join if deemed amenable.
Decline.
Just your average traveller stuck between realms. Pull me out and we'll get properly introduced.
Ten years of bad luck if you kill a wizard. Why take the risk?
Fair enough. Yes, I'd like you to join me after all.
Your lust for blood is rare. Let us hope you know where to direct it.
I attribute it to divine intervention.
Ah, my saviour! I'd be in quite a bind if not for your valiant tugging.

EditorData.NodeContext: Warm/grateful. Follow-up greeting after the player managed to yank him out of a rock he was magically trapped in,

Text.Value: At magic.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Gale wistfully glances behind him at the waypoint, thinking on how close a scrape it was. Foreshaowing of him mourning his former magical skills.

Text.Value: Most excellent! Then without further ado, let's be off!
That's hardly any of your business.
Here's hoping we come across a powerful healer and a powerful wizard both.
A pity. I thought I sensed rapport, the promise of adventure, a flutter of excitement right here in my breadbasket... but perhaps it was merely indigestion.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Gestures towards his abdomen on 'here in my breadbasket'.
EditorData.NodeContext: Disappointed. Player has declined to take him along with them

Text.Value: I'd happily accept, but you're not the leader of your little troupe, are you? Not your call to make, I'm afraid.
And why would I really, really not want attack you?
But even so, I have the unfortunate suspicion your survival is still very much in jeopardy.
By Mystra's eyelids, stop! Cease, you loon! Agh! Agh!
Let flow some words of prayer to soothe the sigil's magic.
Can't say that I am.
Recognising this glimmer to be magical in nature, I reached out to it with a Weaving of words and found myself on the other side as it were.
That vast, burning wreckage behind you somewhat contradicts your story, but here you stand, so who am I to argue?
Say, but I know you, don't I? In a manner of speaking. You were on the nautiloid as well.
Much obliged. Besides, I suspect the real villain here is one we have in common.
So speaking about divine intervention, you don't happen to be a cleric, by any chance, do you? A doctor? Surgeon? Uncannily adroit with a knitting needle?

EditorData.AnimationTags: [ChristianD] Player starts with StandL steps forward to touch the sigil. As soon as the PLYR touches sigil, it sparks and the PLYR immediately retracts their hand in pain.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: (Cine) You reach out to touch the sigil. When you touch it, sparks fly, and you quickly retract your hand in pain, like accidentally touching a red-hot pan.

Text.Value: Gotcha. Private. Nothing to do with me.
*Joy floods through you. You were dazed on the nautiloid. But now you are truly awake, alive.*
Couldn't have phrased it more repellently myself.
My, I hope it has been made abundantly clear that to kill me is... counterproductive.
It's a process known as ceremorphosis, and let me assure you: it is to be avoided.
As we've established, few enough can. It's not exactly a common affliction.
I sense the leadership of your troupe lies elsewhere. I'd be most grateful for an introduction.
At not wasting the time of passing adventurers? I certainly hope so.
As such, I'm feeling magnanimous enough to let bygones be bygones. A healer is what we need. Shall we?
Then I can only assume you too were on the receiving end of a rather unwelcome insertion in the ocular region.
Attune yourself to the sigil's magic, then bid it to quiet down.
I can knit you a cap, but that's where my prowess with the knitting needle stops.
A bit shocked, but friend, it's a relief and a pleasure to make your acquaintance.
The currents of Weave around these sigils are absolutely fascinating. So much to explore!
You'll have to remain extremely calm to touch him without burning him. Take a deep breath, then pull.
Ignore the urge to maim. Grab the hand and pull.
Grab the hand and pull.
At introductions?
Take a deep breath. Stay calm and cool. When you're sure your flames won't hurt him, pull again.
Pull again, as hard as you can.
Go on...
Oh, but I've just come to realise you're not the leader of this little troupe. My joining your ranks is not your call to make, I'm afraid.
We're most certainly going to need a healer, and soon too. How about we lend each other a helping hand once more and look for a healer together?
I'm certain.
Who are you?
Touch the sigil.
To be honest, I haven't a clue.
No, thank you. I'm not looking for another travelling companion.
Whisper to the Weave roiling within the sigil. Attempt to calm it down.
Then it looks like we're both starved for answers.
Back on the ship, you too were on the receiving end of a rather unwelcome insertion in the ocular region, were you not?
Most, no doubt. But I find myself hoping to be in the presence of the few. You don't happen to be one of them?
A hand? Anyone?
Sounds like a plan. You're welcome to join me.
Ooft, hello. I'm Gale of Waterdeep. Apologies, I'm usually better at this.
Accept.
This is more trouble than it's worth. Leave him to his fate.
Fantasise about hacking off the hand.
Sheathe your weapon.
You seem to know enough about our condition to realise it is beyond most clerics' skills.
Exploration merits companionship though. Shall we?
Apologies, I didn't exactly memorise my cephalopodian banishment spells last night. Wasn't the best prepared for an attack-by-squid.
Your quite significant loss. Farewell then, and good luck.
Leave.
Careful! I kept calm before, but touching me could easily kill you.
Whoa. What the fuck just happened?
Poor man! That's no way to treat a stranger in need.
I'll perish...!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: (Cine) The hand disappears into the sparkles and the sigil becomes dormant. A cry of 'I'll perish!' echoes several times, sounding increasingly far away, like an echo. Then silence.

Text.Value: Whoa - easy does it. You really, really don't want to do that. Not a threat, just an observation.
Just full of surprises, aren't you?
No! I can't make it out by myself. I'll perish in here!

Synopsis:
Updated recruitment dialogue for Gale, post-EA. 

Gale's arm appears from the waypoint teleporter near the nautiloid crash site. From the other side of the portal, he asks the player to grab his hand and pull him through. If they help, he can be recruited to the party, and will talk about seeing the players aboard the nautiloid.

There is a Dark Urge moment in this dialogue, in which they can cut off Gale's arm before he is revelaed, killing him.
